featured_reviews.review_id:
Nestled in a remarkably peaceful setting, the only Shia Mosque in Shillong stands as a testament to both serene spirituality and architectural grandeur. Beyond its religious significance, this place offers a holistic experience, embracing education, literature, and community engagement.

The mosque hosts a school committed to providing high-quality education, shaping young minds with a focus on excellence. Adjacent to this educational institution is a sprawling library, housing an extensive collection of books on Islam. What sets this library apart is its inclusivity, featuring materials in a multitude of languages, thereby becoming a beacon of knowledge accessible to a diverse audience.

The architecture extends beyond the prayer halls, with a meticulously designed sitting area that beckons visitors to immerse themselves in the world of literature. The intention behind its layout is evident--a space that not only accommodates reading but encourages it, fostering an atmosphere of reflection and tranquility.

Particularly noteworthy are the Islamic classes held in the library on specific days. This community-oriented initiative further establishes the mosque as a center for both spiritual and intellectual growth. It opens its doors not only to the Muslim community but also extends a warm welcome to individuals of all backgrounds, making it a cultural and educational hub for Shillong.

In essence, this mosque transcends religious boundaries, emerging as a cultural landmark and educational haven. Its architectural magnificence, coupled with a commitment to knowledge and community, renders it a must-visit destination--even for those outside the Muslim faith.

Large and warm Masjid. Toilets are not good and not adequate. Also wudu khana is small but manageable.
The parking hall is big and accommodates a lot of people. In Jummah the 1st floor also gets filled.
Both hanafi and ahle hadis are accepted.
There are food places outside.
It is 300-400M away from the central police bazaar more.
I stayed 100 M away at the popular hotel.

featured_reviews.review_id: I was thinking about searching for masjid. We've reached Police Bajar after Asor and were eating in restaurant named Hotel Savera. Suddenly heard the beautiful sound of Adhaan and I was very happy about this. Completed Salatul Magrib there. Found Muslims from Bangladesh there who were also visiting. This masjid is not so beautiful but it's a center for Muslims. The Adhaan was by speaker and at a lower sound compared to Bangladesh. Not satisfied with the Indian Muslims. We love them, we have a feelings for them. But they are enjoying the Indian nationalism. They are not having a world view. It's my view that Bangladeshi Muslims are better than Indian Muslims in case of feelings for Muslim brothers around the world.
